Most jackets have a variety of '''inner pockets''', and two main '''outer pockets''', which are generally either patch pockets, flap pockets, or jetted pockets.
<ref>The Nu-Way Course in Fashionable Clothes Making (1926). [http://vintagesewing.info/1920s/26-fcm/fcm-33.html Lesson 33]</ref>

[[File:JackePatchPocket.jpg|thumb|left|A patch pocket on a [[blazer|reefer jacket]]]]The patch pocket is, with its single extra piece of cloth sewn directly onto the front of the jacket, a sporting option, sometimes seen on summer linen suits, or other informal styles.

{{Clear}}[[File:JacketFlapPocket.jpg|thumb|left|A jetted pocket with flap on a [[lounge suit]] jacket]]The jetted flap pocket is standard for hip pockets, with a small strip of fabric taping the top and bottom of the slit for the pocket. It has a lined flap of matching fabric covering the top of the pocket, sewn in along the seam of the jetting.  This flap was initially created to protect the contents of the pocket from any rain, and is therefore traditionally meant to be tucked in when indoors, leaving the jettings exposed for show. <ref name="urlHow to choose a single breasted jacket – The Mitchelli – Modern Gentleman">{{cite web | url = http://www.themitchelli.com/2010/11/how-to-choose-a-single-breasted-jacket/ | title = How to choose a single breasted jacket – The Mitchelli – Modern Gentleman | author = | authorlink = | coauthors = | date = | format = | work = | publisher = | pages = | language = | archiveurl = | archivedate = | quote = | accessdate = 2018-02-24}}</ref><ref name="urlGUIDE TO JACKET POCKET STYLE: FLAP, JETTED OR PATCH -">{{cite web | url = https://mrkoachman.com/jacket-pocket-style-flap-jetted-patch/ | title = GUIDE TO JACKET POCKET STYLE: FLAP, JETTED OR PATCH - | author = | authorlink = | coauthors = | date = | format = | work = | publisher = | pages = | language = | archiveurl = | archivedate = | quote = | accessdate = 2018-02-24}}</ref><ref name="urlFlaps no more – I’m taking the last of my suit... | The Silentist">{{cite web | url = http://thesilentist.com/post/102985023791/flaps-no-more-im-taking-the-last-of-my-suit | title = Flaps no more – I’m taking the last of my suit... &#124; The Silentist | author = | authorlink = | coauthors = | date = 24 Nov| format = | work = | publisher = | pages = | language = English| archiveurl = | archivedate = | quote = | accessdate = 2018-02-24}}</ref><ref name="urlThe History of Pockets | The Art of Manliness">{{cite web | url = https://www.artofmanliness.com/2015/05/20/a-mans-pockets/ | title = The History of Pockets &#124; The Art of Manliness | author = | authorlink = | coauthors = | date = | format = | work = | publisher = | pages = | language = | archiveurl = | archivedate = | quote = | accessdate = 2018-02-24}}</ref> However, because this fact is now often ignored and the flap is seen as an accessory that completes the style, it is commonly left out indoors, even during formal events.

{{Clear}}[[File:JacketJettedPocket.jpg|thumb|left|A jetted pocket on a [[dinner jacket]]]]A jetted pocket with no flap is most formal. This style is most often on seen on [[formalwear]], such as a [[dinner jacket]].

{{Clear}}In addition to the standard two outer pockets, some suits have a third, the ticket pocket, usually located just above the right pocket and roughly half as wide.  While this was originally exclusively a feature of country suits, used for conveniently storing a train ticket, it is now seen on some town suits. Another country feature also worn sometimes in cities is a pair of hacking pockets, which are similar to normal ones, but slanted; this was originally designed to make the pockets easier to open on horseback while hacking, also called [[pleasure riding]].<ref name="Flusser85ch2">Flusser (1985). [http://www.throughtherye.com/flusser/ch2.htm ch. 2]</ref><ref name="BespokeOptions">Bookster, a manufacturer of tweed jackets, has illustrations of various features of jackets: {{cite web | url = http://www.tweed-jacket.com/GALLERY%20PAGE/Bespoke%20Options/index.htm | title = Jacket options | accessdate = 2008-09-20}}</ref>

