'''Turkey City Writer's Workshop''' is a peer-to-peer, professional science fiction writer's workshop in Texas.  Founded in 1973 and still ongoing today, it was consciously modeled after the east coast [[Milford Writer's Workshop]].<ref name="homepage">[http://home.roadrunner.com/~lperson1/TC.html The Turkey City Writer's Workshop Homepage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323060310/http://home.roadrunner.com/~lperson1/TC.html |date=March 23, 2009 }}</ref> The workshop "was a cradle of cyberpunk"<ref name="lexicon">{{Cite web | last = Sterling | first = Bruce | authorlink = Bruce Sterling |author2=Lewis Shiner  | title = Turkey City Lexicon: A Primer for SF Workshops | publisher = SFWA | url = http://www.sfwa.org/2009/06/turkey-city-lexicon-a-primer-for-sf-workshops/ | accessdate = 2010-10-08}}</ref> where many of the practitioners of what would become cyberpunk first met.<ref>{{Citation | last = Swanwick | first = Michael | author-link = Michael Swanwick | title = A User's Guide to the Postmoderns | journal = Isaac Asimov's Science Fiction Magazine | pages = 24 |date=August 1986}}</ref>

Founding members of the group included [[Lisa Tuttle]], [[Howard Waldrop]], [[Steven Utley]], and [[Tom Reamy]].  The workshop was first held in [[Grand Prairie, Texas]], but soon shifted to [[Austin]] when most of the writers involved moved there during the mid-1970s. [[Bruce Sterling]] was one of the youngest members of the workshop when he joined it in 1974.<ref name="dmn971109"/><ref>Lambert et al. 2005. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=qi-ItIG6QLwC&pg=PA220&lpg=PA220&dq=Turkey+City+Writers+Workshop&source=bl&ots=uwWLAzS6FJ&sig=Z0jhH0hRFmyMZoZ6G2O56947Oe8&hl=en&ei=88mvTP7HKsn_nQftucz5BQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CD0Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=Turkey%20City%20Writers%20Workshop&f=false The Internet: A Historical Encyclopedia]''. New York: MTM Publishing. p 220.</ref> [[Harlan Ellison]] "discovered" Sterling at Turkey City and arranged for the publication of his first novel.<ref name="dmn971109"/> Other writers who have attended Turkey City include [[Ted Chiang]], [[Paul Di Filippo]], [[Cory Doctorow]], [[Andy Duncan (writer)|Andy Duncan]], [[George Alec Effinger]], [[Mark Finn]], [[Steven Gould]], [[Eileen Gunn]], [[Leigh Kennedy]], [[John Kessel]], [[Rick Klaw]], [[Raph Koster]], [[George R. R. Martin]], [[Maureen McHugh]], [[Paul O. Miles]], [[Chris Nakashima-Brown]], [[Chad Oliver]], [[Lawrence Person]], [[Jessica Reisman]], [[Chris Roberson (author)|Chris Roberson]], [[Jayme Lynn Blaschke]], [[Lewis Shiner]], [[Lou Antonelli]], [[John Shirley]], [[Jeff VanderMeer]],<ref>http://primastoria.com/feature/interview-with-jeff-vandermeer Jeff VanderMeer interview, citing workshop inspiration for a novel.</ref> [[Don Webb (writer)|Don Webb]], [[Martha Wells]], and [[Connie Willis]].<ref name="homepage" />

The workshop also compiled "The Turkey City Lexicon," a collection of terms used when discussing recurring SF writing tropes.<ref name=lexicon/><ref>[http://www.critters.org/turkeycity.html Turkey City Lexicon (original)]</ref> This guide for writers has been used and adapted by other writers workshops, both within and outside the science fiction genre.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Slug City Writers | title = Tom Swifties and Other Writing Sins | work = Bucks County Writers Workshop | url = http://donswaim.com/writers.swifties.html | accessdate = 2010-10-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last = Duane | first = Diane | authorlink = Diane Duane |author2=Peter Morwood  | title = Writers' Workshop Background | pages = 23 | url = http://www.owlspringspartnership.com/workshop/NADWC_Writers_Workshop_handout_2009.pdf}}</ref>
